{"title_page": "Bizerte", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n| official_name            = Bizerte\n| native_name              = {{lang|ar|\u0628\u0646\u0632\u0631\u062a}}\n| other_name               = \n|settlement_type        = [[List of cities in Tunisia|City]]\n| image_skyline            = CityHallBizerte.JPG\n| imagesize                = 260px\n| image_caption            = Bizerte City Hall in Belgique Street area\n| image_flag               =\n| flag_size                = 120px\n| image_seal               =\n| image_shield             = \n| shield_size              = 100px\n| nickname                 =\n| motto                    =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n| image_map                =\n| map_caption              =\n| pushpin_map              = Tunisia\n| pushpin_label_position   = top\n| pushpin_map_caption      = Location in Tunisia\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n| coordinates              = {{coord|37|16|40|N|9|51|50|E|region:TN|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{TUN}}\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Governorates of Tunisia|Governorate]]\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Bizerte Governorate]]\n| subdivision_type2        =\n| subdivision_name2        =\n| subdivision_type3        =\n| subdivision_name3        =\n| subdivision_type4        =\n| subdivision_name4        =\n| established_title        = <!-- Settled -->\n| established_date         =\n| government_type          = [[Mayor]]\n| government_footnotes     =\n| leader_title             =\n| leader_name              =\n| area_footnotes           =\n| area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n| area_total_sq_mi         =\n| area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n| area_land_sq_mi          =\n| area_water_km2           =\n| area_water_sq_mi         =\n| area_water_percent       =\n| area_urban_km2           = 34<ref name=\"STRAT\">{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.commune-bizerte.gov.tn Mnicipalit\u00e9 de Bizerte]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104111052/http://www.commune-bizerte.gov.tn/ |date=January 4, 2010  }}.</ref>\n| area_urban_sq_mi         = 13.127\n| elevation_footnotes      = <!--for references: use<ref> </ref>  tags-->\n| elevation_m              = 5<ref>[http://dateandtime.info/citycoordinates.php?id=2472706 City Coordinates (Dateandtime.info)]</ref>\n| elevation_ft             = 16\n| population_footnotes     =\n| population_total         = 142,966<ref name=\"STRAT\"/>\n| population_as_of         = 2014<ref name=\"STRAT\"/>\n| population_density_km2   = 3,363\n| population_density_sq_mi = 8,712\n| population_metro         = 401,144\n| population_note          =\n| timezone                 = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset               = +01:00\n| timezone_DST             =\n| utc_offset_DST           =\n| postal_code_type         = Postal code\n| postal_code              = 7000\n| area_code                = [[+216]] (Tun)  72  (Bizerte)\n| website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20100104111052/http://www.commune-bizerte.gov.tn/ www.commune-bizerte.gov.tn]\n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Bizerte''' or '''Bizerta''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0646\u0632\u0631\u062a}} ''{{audio|help=no|Benzart.wav|Benzart}}''), the [[classical antiquity|classical]] '''Hippo''', is a town of [[Bizerte Governorate]] in [[Tunisia]]. It is the [[List of northernmost items|northernmost]] city in Africa, located 65&nbsp;km (40mil) north of the capital [[Tunis]]. It is one of the oldest known settlements in Tunisia, having been founded by settlers from the [[Phoenicia]]n port of [[Sidon]] around 1100{{nbsp}}BC. It is also known as the last town to remain under [[French Tunisia|French control]] after the rest of the country won its independence from [[France]]. The city had 142,966 inhabitants in 2014.\n\n{{anchor|Etymology|Name}}\n\n==Names==\nHippo is the [[latinization of names|latinization]] of a [[Punic language|Punic]]<ref name=\"Dr Mahmoud ABIDIfrench\"/><ref name=\"ORIGIN\">[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0059:entry=Hippo&highlight=hippo Perseus Digital Library].</ref> name ({{lang-xpu|\ud802\udd0f\ud802\udd10\ud802\udd05{{popdf}}\ud802\udd0d}}, {{smallcaps|\u02bfpwn}}),{{sfnp|Ghaki|2015|p=66}} probably related to the word ''\u00fbb\u00f4n'', meaning \"harbor\".{{sfnp|Brown|2013|p=326}} To distinguish it from [[Hippo Regius]] (the modern [[Annaba]], in [[Algeria]]), the Greeks and Romans used several epithets. [[Scylax of Caryanda]] mentions it as '''{{nowrap|Hippo Acra}}''' and {{nowrap|Hippo Polis}} (\"Hippo the City\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ccibizerte.org/page.php?r=1&ssr=&sr=2|title=Chambre de Commerce et d'Industrie du Nord-Est Bizerte|last=Tunisia|first=Stelfair|website=www.ccibizerte.org|access-date=2018-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Dr Mahmoud ABIDIfrench\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bizerteyahasra.com|title=bizerteyahasra|author=Dr Mahmoud ABIDI(french)|date=2008-02-05|publisher=bizerteyahasra.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809112509/http://www.bizerteyahasra.com/|archivedate=August 9, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-10-13}}</ref> [[Polybius]] mentions it as {{nowrap|'''Hippo Diarrhytus'''}} ({{lang-grc-gre|\u1f39\u03c0\u03c0\u1f7c\u03bd \u03b4\u03b9\u03ac\u03c1\u03c1\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2}}, ''Hipp\u014dn Di\u00e1rrhytos''), \"Hippo Divided-by-the-Water\", in reference to the town's prominent [[canal]].<ref name=\"ORIGIN\"/> It also appears in [[Roman Empire|Roman]], [[Vandals|Vandal]], and [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] sources as {{nowrap|'''Hippo Zarytus'''}}.<ref name=\"STTRAT\">[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0234:book=1:chapter=70&highlight=hippo Hippo Zarytus(in Perseus Digital Library)].</ref> Its Arabic name '''Banzart''' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0646\u0632\u0631\u062a}}) and the [[French language|French]] and [[English language|English]] forms derived from it all represent phonetic developments of its ancient name.<ref name=\"Dr Mahmoud ABIDIfrench\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Vue a\u00e9rienne de Bizerte.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Aerial view of Bizerte (October 2008)]]\n[[File:PhoenicianTrade.png|thumb|right|200px|[[Phoenicia]]n trade routes 1200 BC \u2013 539 BC ]]\n[[File:GiorcesBardo46.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Roman mosaic with scenes of fishing and village life ([[Bardo National Museum]], [[Tunisia]])]]\n[[Phoenicia]]ns from [[Sidon]] founded Bizerte, one of the oldest cities in [[Tunisia]], around 1100{{nbsp}}BC.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.bizerteyahasra.com/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130809112509/http://www.bizerteyahasra.com/|url-status= dead|archive-date= 2013-08-09|title= Bizerte, Ya Hasra, le blog de Mahmoud ABIDI|date= 2013-08-09|access-date= 2018-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://bizerteyahasra.over-blog.com/page/2|title= Bizerte, Ya Hasra, le blog de Mahmoud ABIDI|last= ABIDI|first= M|website= Bizerte, Ya Hasra, le blog de Mahmoud ABIDI|language= fr-FR|access-date= 2018-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Antiquity : (1100 BC to 647 AD)===\n[[File:Phoenician ship.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Phoenician ship carved on the face of a sarcophagus. 2nd century AD.]]\n* Initially a small [[Phoenicia]]n harbor for [[thalassocracy|maritime trading]] in the western [[Mediterranean]], the settlement lay 30&nbsp;km (18.5 mil) north of [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]] and 50&nbsp;km (31 mil) northwest of [[Carthage]], other cities founded by Phoenicians.\nAround 950 BC the city came under the influence of Carthage during the reign of [[Dido (Queen of Carthage)|Queen Dido/Elissa]], In 309 BC, during the [[Greek\u2013Punic Wars]] and after the defeat of [[Agathocles]], the city and Sicily returned to the [[Carthaginian Republic]]. Several Carthaginian generals used its port during the [[Punic Wars]] of 264-146 BC - such as [[Hamilcar Barca]], [[Mago (Barcid)|Mago]], [[Hasdrubal (Barcid)|Hasdrubal]] and [[Hannibal]].\n* In 149 BC the first Roman raids occurred. During the ascendancy of [[Julius Caesar]] the  [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] occupied the city, calling it Hippo Diarrhytus. The city regained its prosperity and progress from the reign of [[Augustus]] (Emperor from 27 BC to 14 AD) and  maintained maritime relations with [[Ostia Antica|Ostia]] and [[Ancient Rome|Rome]], as shown by a mosaic decorating its commercial representation in the square of [[Piazzale delle Corporazioni|Forum of Corporations]]. Christianity spread in the city under the Empire.\n* In 439 AD [[Genseric]], the king of the [[Vandals]] ([[Germanic peoples|East Germanic tribes]]) and his followers invaded the city and used the port as a base for invasions into other parts of the [[Western Roman Empire]]: the city of Rome and the islands of [[Sardinia]], [[Malta]], [[Corsica]] and [[Sicily]]. The town appears on the medieval [[Peutinger Map]].\n* From 534 AD to 642 AD the city came under the control of the [[Byzantine Empire]] after a defeat of the Vandals in 534; they{{who|date=July 2019}} build the Fort of Bizerte (now the Fort of Kasba).\n\n[[File:BizerteKasba.jpg|thumb|right|Old Port of Bizerte]]\n[[File:Pilsum leaving Bizerte.jpg|thumb|right|The moveable bridge of the Bizerte canal]]\n\n===Later history===\n[[Rashidun Caliphate|Arab]] armies took Bizerte in 647 in their first invasion of the area, but the city reverted to control from Constantinople until the Byzantines were defeated and finally driven from North Africa in 695\u201398. The troops of [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] captured the city in 1535; the [[Conquest of Tunis (1574)|Turks took it in 1574]]. The city then became a [[Barbary Pirate|corsair]] harbour and struggled against the French and the Venetians.\n\nWith its occupation of Tunisia in 1881, [[French Third Republic|France]] gained control of Bizerte and built a large naval harbour in the city.\n\nIn 1924, after the French government officially recognized the [[Soviet Union]] (USSR), [[Wrangel's fleet|the western military fleet of White Russia]] that had been kept in the port of Bizerte was returned to the Soviet government. The ships were never moved from the port and finally were sold there as scrap metal.\n\nIn March 1939, towards the end of the [[Spanish Civil War]], [[Spanish Republican Navy]] Commander [[Miguel Buiza Fern\u00e1ndez-Palacios|Miguel Buiza]] ordered the evacuation of the bulk of the Republican fleet. Three cruisers, eight destroyers and two submarines left [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]] harbor and reached Bizerte, where the French authorities impounded them.<ref>{{cite book |authorlink= Hugh Thomas (writer) |last= Thomas |first= Hugh |title= The Spanish Civil War\n| publisher = [[Penguin Books]] |year= 2001 |location= London |page= 877}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[World War II|Second World War]], the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German]] and [[Royal Italian Army|Italian armies]] occupied Bizerte until [[Tunisian Campaign|Allied troops defeated them]] on 7 May 1943. During the fighting between the [[Allies of World War II|Allied forces]] and the German Army, many of the city's inhabitants fled to the countryside or to [[Tunis]]. The city suffered significant damage during the battle.<ref>{{cite web\n |url= http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/bizerte/bizerte-fm.htm\n |title= To Bizerte With The Ii Corps\n |publisher= History.army.mil\n |date= \n |accessdate= 2012-08-04\n |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120726133335/http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/bizerte/bizerte-fm.htm\n |archive-date= 2012-07-26\n |url-status= dead\n }}</ref>\n[[File:Vue a\u00e9rienne de Bizerte - 1959.jpg|thumb|right|180px| Aerial view of Bizerte in 1959]]\nDue to Bizerte's strategic location on the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], [[French Fourth Republic|France]] retained control of the city and her naval base after Tunisian independence in 1956. \nIn 1961 Tunisian forces [[Bizerte crisis|blockaded]] the area of Bizerte and demanded French withdrawal. The face-off turned nasty when a French helicopter took off and drew fire.   The French brought in reinforcements; when these were fired upon, France took decisive military action against the Tunisian forces. Using state-of-the-art weapons and decisive force the French took Bizerte and [[Menzel Bourguiba]].  During three days in July 1961, 700 Tunisians died (1200 wounded); the French lost 24 dead (100 wounded).{{citation needed|date= July 2014}}\n\nMeetings at the [[United Nations Security Council|UN Security Council]] and other international pressure moved France to agreement; the French military finally abandoned Bizerte on 15 October 1963.{{citation needed|date= July 2014}}\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Location===\nBizerte is on a section of widened inlet and east-facing coast of the north coast of Tunisia, 15 kilometres from [[Ras ben Sakka]] (the northernmost point in Africa on the [[Mediterranean Sea]]), 20 kilometers northeast of the [[Ichkeul lake]] (a World Heritage Site), 30 kilometers (18 miles) north of the archaeological site of [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]] and 65 kilometers north of [[Tunis]].\n\nit has to the west coastal hills forming an outcrop of the [[Tell Atlas]] with well-conserved woods and vantage points.  Its associated beaches include Sidi Salem, La Grotte, Rasenjela, and Al Rimel.  It is on a section of Mediterranean climate coastline, close to [[Sardinia]] and [[Sicily]], as opposed to coasts in the south of the country which have a year-round dry desert climate.\n\nThe city is centered on the north shore of the canal of Bizerte linking the Mediterranean Sea to a tidal lake, the [[Lac de Bizerte]] which is larger than all parts of the town combined, to the immediate south.  Built-up areas are in three directions:\n*South-west along the widening canal with jetties at Pecherie and Jarrouba, the latter associated with [[Bizerte-Sidi Ahmed Air Base]] adjoining the opening of the lake and military/rescue heliport.  \n*North are Sidi Salam and Corniche. They are within meters of the coast and on coast-facing slopes of the Ain Berda, a range of hills toward Cap Blanc, a small headland in the Ain Damou Plage natural conservation area. \n*Zarzouna, [[Menzel Jemil]] and [[Menzel Abderrahmane]] are on the south shore of the canal, formed by the locality of Zarzouna and the towns of [[Menzel Jemil]] and [[Menzel Abderrahmane]], by a moveable bridge and both Menzels face the lake itself.  The rest of the [[isthmus]] on which they stand is the gently rising Foret de Remel, reaching a high point east of its forest area at [[Cap Zebib]].\n\n===Transport===\nThe bridge leads to [[A4 motorway (Tunisia)|the motorway A4]] leading to [[Tunis\u2013Carthage International Airport]] and the capital. On the town side the P11 passes semi-rural Louata, hugs Ichkeul Lake and branches into a western route, the P7, leading directly to [[Tabarka]] on the coast next to the Algerian border.  The P11 leads south-west to [[B\u00e9ja]], a governorate center, in the foothills of the [[Tell Atlas]], forks into several roads at [[Bou Salem]], a small town in a broad fertile plain, and climbs to Firnanah passing two high-altitude lakes and also approaching the north-west border with Algeria.\n\n===Climate===\nBizerte enjoys a [[Mediterranean climate#Hot-summer Mediterranean climate|hot-summer mediterranean]] climate, with mild, rainy winters and hot, dry summers. The Mediterranean Sea breeze makes summers cooler but more humid.<ref name=\"Climate\u2013Data.Eu\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.climatedata.eu/climate.php?loc=tsxx0001&lang=en |title=Climate Bizerte \u2013 Table|publisher=Climate\u2013Data.Eu|accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| location = Bizerte (1981\u20132010, extremes 1901\u20132017)\n| Jan record high C = 